aVEnemies of Israel have swapped terrorism for political warfare in a bid to destroy the Jewish State \u2013 and it is all taking place at the United Nations, Alex Ryvchin, editor of "The Anti-Israel Agenda: Inside the Political War on the Jewish State," told Newsmax TV on Monday.\u000a\u000a"The United Nations is very much ground zero of the new internationalized war on the Jewish state," Ryvchin told Newsmax's J.D. Hayworth. ". . . They tried to destroy the state from within through terrorism. And when that failed, they opened a new frontier, which is this political war.\u000a\u000a"The U.N. played such a key role in the creation of Israel through passing the resolution in 1947 calling for the creation of two states, a Jewish state and an Arab state living side by side in peace. But in recent years it has become probably the chief purveyor of propaganda, of slurs, of the efforts to isolate and cripple the state."\u000a\u000aImportant: Newsmax TV is available on DirecTV Ch. 349, U-Verse 1220, and FiOS 615. If your cable operator does not have Newsmax TV just call and ask them to put us on \u2013 Call toll-free 1-844-500-6397 and we will connect you right away to your cable operator!\u000a\u000aFor more places to Find Newsmax TV \u2013 Click Here Now\u000a\u000aRyvchin, a Ukraine-born Jew who migrated to Australia as a refugee, believes Europe has regressed in its allegiance with Israel and is "seeking to embrace the forces that Israel fights."\u000a\u000a"That is really remarkable for a number of reasons," he told Hayworth. "We can talk about Europe's role in the genocide of the Jews 70 years ago, but more so more to the point is that Europe shares the same liberal democratic values that Israel has.\u000a\u000a"And it is the one state in the region that has those values. And for those reasons Europe and Israel should be natural partners in all respects particularly in security. Israel stands at the vanguard of the fight against Islamic terrorism. Something that has been brought home to European shores now.\u000a\u000a"It really is quite difficult to understand why Europe is taking an increasingly hostile line towards Israel rather than moving closer towards it."\u000a\u000aPart of the change is due to "the new wave of migration" to Europe \u2013 and particularly that of the past 10 years from North Africa and parts of the Middle East, he said.\u000a\u000a"[It has] changed the composition of Europe and that will have bearing on the politics of Europe, there's no doubt about that."\u000a\u000aThat said, Russian President Vladimir Putin "is said to be well disposed of the Jewish community in Russia," according to Ryvchin.\u000a\u000a"Relations with Israel are getting stronger and closer," he said. "The Israeli president visited last year. The prime minister was there this year and delegations frequently go over and address the Russian parliament as well. This really, in my view, comes down to political expediency.\u000a\u000a"I think it's a desire to reclaim some sort of neo-Soviet Empire in the east and beyond."\u000a\u000a"The Anti-Israel Agenda: Inside the Political War on the Jewish State," published by Gefen, brings together such scholars of the Arab-Israeli conflict as Alan Dershowitz, Alan Johnson, Col. Richard Kemp, and Hillel Neuer.
