aVBERLIN (AP) \u2014 A court has nixed the minimum height requirement for police recruits in Germany's most populous state, arguing that it is unfair to men.\u000a\u000aThe case was brought by a female applicant who was rejected because she is 161.5 centimeters (5 feet 3 inches) tall.\u000a\u000aThat's 1.5 centimeters shorter than the minimum height required of women, which is 163 centimeters. Male police recruits in North Rhine-Westphalia state have to be at least 168 centimeters tall.\u000a\u000aDuesseldorf administrative court judges noted Tuesday that the state's differing height requirements were introduced to correct the gender imbalance among applicants, which is skewed toward men.\u000a\u000aIn disqualifying the height requirement for men, the court automatically eliminated it for women too.\u000a\u000aThe court ordered authorities to reinstate the application of the 22-year-old plaintiff, Johanna Fee Dillmann.
p159
aVSupport for a "clean" debt ceiling increase is a "tough sell" for Republicans, according to Rep. Tom Cole, R-Okla.\u000a\u000a"Most Republicans want to do something to lower the trajectory of the debt. I mean, a clean debt ceiling hike is like having a credit card and saying 'I've reached my limit, I'm just going to change the limit higher without changing any of my spending habits,'" Cole said Tuesday on MSNBC's "Morning Joe."\u000a\u000a"That's a tough sell to Republicans. Democrats seem to be fine with that, but I think most of my colleagues aren't," Cole said on the MSNBC show.\u000a\u000aCole noted that President Donald Trump's administration had called for a clean hike.\u000a\u000a"What administration doesn't ask for that?" Cole said in the interview.\u000a\u000aThe congressman said that he wants a measure to increase the debt ceiling, but he wants to add policies that will improve government spending and debt rules.\u000a\u000a"This idea we can go on spending interminably and just simply raise the debt ceiling every time \u2014 sooner or later the credit markets are going to make that impossible to do. So let's reassure them and show them we're serious about lowering the deficits and eventually the long-term debt," Cole said in the "Morning Joe" interview.\u000a\u000aRep. Mark Meadows, R-N.C., agreed with Cole on Thursday.\u000a\u000a"There is no reason that when Republicans control the House, the Senate, and the White House that the debt ceiling should be lifted without putting in place measures to get a hold of our out-of-control spending and address our national debt," Meadows said in The Daily Beast.\u000a\u000aCongress' deadline for a debt ceiling increase is Sept. 29, according to The Hill.
p160
aVGen. John Kelly will crack the whip and bring discipline to the White House in his new role as President Donald Trump's chief of staff \u2014 but don't expect him to be able to rein his boss in, veteran political journalist and bestselling author Edward Klein told Newsmax TV on Tuesday.\u000a\u000a"No one, including Donald Trump's father, Fred Trump, has ever been able to rein in Donald Trump. I've known Donald Trump for 35 years and he's never been different than he is today," Klein said to Miranda Khan on Newsmax's "America Talks Live."\u000a\u000a"Even if Gen. Kelly can rein in Ivanka [Trump] and Jared [Kushner] and [Steve] Bannon and the entire White House staff, he's not going to be able to rein in Donald Trump, who believes by being unpresidential is how he became president.\u000a\u000a"So what you're going to see is a president who continues as he has in the past to be unconventional, but the White House staff is going to be very disciplined, which should be very interesting to see how this works out."\u000a\u000aImportant: Newsmax TV is available on DirecTV Ch. 349, U-Verse 1220, and FiOS 615. If your cable operator doesn't have Newsmax TV just call and ask them to put us on \u2013 Call toll-free 1-844-500-6397 and we'll connect you right away to your cable operator!\u000a\u000aFor more places to Find Newsmax TV \u2013 Click Here Now\u000a\u000aKelly replaced Reince Priebus as chief of staff following a tumultuous week during which Priebus was ousted, and Anthony "The Mooch" Scaramucci was appointed communications chief, only to be fired.\u000a\u000aKlein said Scaramucci \u2014 who got the ax after his profanity-filled rant against Priebus and Bannon in an interview with the New Yorker \u2014 was "sort of a metaphor about everything that was going wrong in the White House.\u000a\u000a"He was amateur who had no political experience and this has been a White House filled with people who have had no previous experience. He was so arrogant that he didn't know what he didn't know, which is always a terrible thing. And finally he reinforced Donald Trump's worst instincts.\u000a\u000a"Now, compare him, say, with Kellyanne Conway who is in the running for that job. When she goes on television, you don't hear her trying to make herself more important. She always talks about how great Donald Trump is and I think that's a key to that job."\u000a\u000aKlein said there is only one "star" in the White House \u2014 Trump himself \u2014 which should be a "warning" to Kelly.\u000a\u000a"Now if Gen. Kelly starts getting great press, which he already started getting, and he suddenly emerges as the star in the White House, I'm not so sure Donald Trump is going to like that," Klein told Khan.\u000a\u000aKlein said Trump liked Scaramucci at first because of his "blatant attacks and kind of macho attitude."\u000a\u000a"But when he realized that this was something that was not going down well not only with his base \u2014 especially because of that profanity \u2014 but also with the Republican Party, I think he then stepped away from Scaramucci," he said.\u000a\u000a"I think it was a brilliant move on the part of Gen. Kelly to say the first thing I'm going to do is get rid of the Mooch and I think it was a wise thing."\u000a\u000aKlein is author of "Guilty as Sin: Uncovering New Evidence of Corruption and How Hillary Clinton and the Democrats Derailed the FBI Investigation," published by Regnery.
